		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Magnetoencephalography</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Magnetoencephalography</b> (<b>MEG</b>) is an imaging technique used to measure the <a href="/wiki/Magnetic_field" title="Magnetic field">magnetic fields</a> produced by electrical activity in the <a href="/wiki/Human_brain" title="Human brain">brain</a> via extremely sensitive devices such as <a href="/wiki/SQUID" title="SQUID">superconducting quantum interference devices</a> (SQUIDs). These measurements are commonly used in both research and clinical settings. There are many uses for the MEG, including assisting surgeons in localizing a pathology, assisting researchers in determining the function of various parts of the brain, <a href="/wiki/Neurofeedback" title="Neurofeedback">neurofeedback</a>, and others.</p>
